<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="12" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="12">
Family 
<taxonomicName LSID="22BD6F0D-147C-5F50-844B-123996602606" authority="Rafinesque, 1815" authorityName="Rafinesque" authorityYear="1815" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Neritidae Rafinesque, 1815</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="12" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="12">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Montfort" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Theodoxus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Theodoxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Neritina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Neritina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are distinguished from each other by their ontogeny (
<bibRefCitation author="Bandel, K" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen aus dem Geologisch-Palaeontologischen Institut der Universitaet Hamburg." pageId="19" pageNumber="30" pagination="65 - 164" refId="B5" refString="Bandel, K, 2001. The history of Theodoxus and Neritina connected with description and systematic evaluation of related Neritimorpha (Gastropoda). Mitteilungen aus dem Geologisch-Palaeontologischen Institut der Universitaet Hamburg. 85: 65 - 164" title="The history of Theodoxus and Neritina connected with description and systematic evaluation of related Neritimorpha (Gastropoda)." volume="85" year="2001">Bandel 2001</bibRefCitation>
). While the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Montfort" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Theodoxus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Theodoxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species hatch from the spawn as miniature adult, 
<taxonomicName genus="Nertina" lsidName="" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Nertina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species leave their spawn as planktotrophic larva that will float in the sea for a more or less extended period before its metamorphosis to a crawling young. However, at the adult stage the taxonomic separation of species of the genera 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Montfort" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Theodoxus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Theodoxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Neritina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Neritina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not always easy. As most of the 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Neritina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Neritina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. are marine species and usually have a denticulate border of the columella and two apophysis of the operculum, most species of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Montfort" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Theodoxus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Theodoxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are limnic and have a smooth border of the columella and one apophysis (the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“rib”">&quot;rib&quot;</normalizedToken>
); some also have a small apophysis, the peg, on the operculum (
<bibRefCitation author="Gloeer, P" journalOrPublisher="Die Tierwelt Deutschlands" pageId="19" pageNumber="30" refId="B22" refString="Gloeer, P, 2002. Die Suesswassergastropoden Nord- und Mitteleuropas. Bestimmungsschluessel, Lebensweise, Verbreitung. Die Tierwelt Deutschlands 73, 327 pp." title="Die Suesswassergastropoden Nord- und Mitteleuropas. Bestimmungsschluessel, Lebensweise, Verbreitung." volume="73" year="2002">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Glöer">Gloeer</normalizedToken>
2002
</bibRefCitation>
). Further, in 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Neritina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Neritina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the peg is thick and strong, while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Montfort" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Theodoxus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Theodoxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is, if exists at all, small and weak. A revision of this family, particularly its subdivion in clearly defined genera is needed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
